# Pingpin Agents ‚Äî Changelog

Daily dev log for the Etsy Enamel Pin multi-agent system (Condition C). Newest entry on top.

---

## 2026-06-27 ‚Äî Agent 3: Drafting agent with feedback loop

**Role:** Agent 3 is the copywriter ‚Äî it fuses every upstream signal into a `title` + `description`. It's the point where all prior agents' outputs converge.

**Design decisions:**
- **One base prompt + conditional append (route B), not two separate prompts.** The standard to meet (Etsy rules, word count, keyword coverage) is identical on the first pass and on a retry ‚Äî what changes is the *material*, not the strictness. First pass = "write from scratch"; retry = "revise against feedback." Keeping one base prompt avoids maintaining the Etsy rules / tone block in two places (single source of truth).
- **Retry logic via `retry_count`:** if `retry_count == 0`, run first-pass generation (fuse A2 signals + own data + tone). If `retry_count >= 1`, append a feedback block to the base prompt ‚Äî last draft (`draft_title` / `draft_description`) + `system_feedback` from A4 ‚Äî and instruct targeted revision.
- **No separate memory for A3.** State *is* the memory: A1/A2 outputs persist in state, so when A4 routes back to A3, A3 re-reads `keyword_list` / `selling_point` etc. directly ‚Äî A1 and A2 do **not** re-run. The retry edge is `A4 ‚Üí A3`, not `A4 ‚Üí A1`.
- **Tone handling:** if the user supplied a `tone_preference`, fold it into the prompt; if blank, let the LLM self-determine a market-appropriate tone (Python decides which branch, not the LLM).

**Code:**
- Implemented `construct_draft_prompt` with structured XML tags guiding the LLM output, improving generation quality and robustness.
- Used a Pydantic `BaseModel` + `re` (regex) to cleanly split title and description into separate fields instead of parsing one blob of text.
- State-aware generation wired through `retry_count` + `system_feedback`, giving A3 the ability to self-iterate based on audit results.

**State management understanding (consolidated):**
- Confirmed the mental model: `State` is a shared dict; read with `state.get()` / `state[]`. Data written by any node persists for all later nodes ‚Äî that's what makes the A4‚ÜíA3 retry loop work without re-running A1/A2.
- Division of labor locked in: A1 = gatekeeper (compliance veto), A2 = material extractor (SEO signals), A3 = copy synthesizer.

**Engineering fixes:**
- Resolved the `if __name__ == "__main__":` logic trap (the earlier quoted-string version that never ran) and cleaned up function scope for proper modularity.
- Fixed `main.py` workflow logic: removed a duplicate edge and repaired the conditional edge so the graph forms a proper closed loop.
- Added defensive handling for `KeyError` and regex-match failures; addressed unreachable-code (greyed-out) static-analysis hints.

**Still pending after today:**
- A3‚ÜîA4 loop isn't closeable until A4 exists ‚Äî `retry_count` increment ownership needs to be nailed down (leaning: A4 increments on reject, A3 only reads).
- `main.py` still needs `workflow.compile()` + an end-to-end invocation entrypoint before the A1‚ÜíA2‚ÜíA3 trunk can actually run start to finish.

---

## 2026-06-26 ‚Äî Agent 2: Designed and implemented from scratch

**Problem identified:**
User-pasted competitor listing text can be noisy ‚Äî marketing fluff, social media links, malformed/poorly structured text. This must not flow into Agent 3 unfiltered, or generated copy quality drops.

**Design decisions:**
- Agent 2 reframed as a **Quality Gate**, not just a data collector ‚Äî it sanitizes before it extracts.
- Adopted a **Signal Extraction Pattern**: instead of manual `if`-gates (hard to maintain, easy to over-strip useful terms like "Personalized"), let the LLM do semantic categorization via a structured-output contract.
- Defined `CompetitorSignal` (Pydantic `BaseModel`) as the data contract:
  - `is_valid: bool` ‚Äî hard pass/fail flag (noise / no product attributes ‚Üí `False`)
  - `keywords: List[str]` ‚Äî deduplicated
  - `selling_points: List[str]` ‚Äî material, size, use-case
  - `reasoning: str` ‚Äî audit trail for why something passed/failed
- **Rejected ChromaDB/vector store for A2.** Competitor text is a single short pasted listing ‚Äî no retrieval needed, just send it straight into the LLM's context window. Vector stores are for A1's use case (searching hundreds of policy pages), not for passing one short string through state.
- **Data priority rule confirmed:** when both own-shop historical conversion data and competitor data exist, own data is "ground truth" and takes priority over competitor data ("market signal," speculative).
- **Manual-paste-first confirmed** for competitor data collection ‚Äî no scraping, which also keeps the project clear of Etsy's ToS restrictions on automated data collection (covered in an earlier discussion).

**Code:**
- First draft of `seo_agent_node(state)` written: reads `competitor_data` from state, calls `structured_llm.invoke()`, writes back `keyword_list` / `selling_point` / `seo_metadata`.
- Code review caught and fixed: unused leftover import from A1 (`persist_directory`), dead code line (`competitor_data = f"state[HumanMessage]"` did nothing, removed), unused imports left over from the dropped Chroma approach (`Chroma`, `PyPDFDirectoryLoader`, splitters, etc.).
- **Not yet fixed:** `if "__name__" == "__main__":` ‚Äî the quotes around `__name__` mean this condition is never true. Needs the quotes removed. *(Fixed 06-27.)*
- **Not yet resolved:** state class name is spelled three different ways across files ‚Äî `pingpingostate`, `PinpingoState`, `pinpingostate`. Must be locked to one spelling project-wide before anything will import cleanly.

**Environment fixes:**
- Resolved a venv/PATH issue: `pip`/`python3` were resolving to the Homebrew global install instead of the project's `.venv`. Fixed by deleting and recreating `.venv`, then re-activating.
- Confirmed `.gitignore` correctly excludes `.env`, `.venv/`, and private data folders from git tracking; covered `git rm -r --cached <folder>` for the case where something was committed before `.gitignore` existed.

---

## 2026-06-25 ‚Äî A1 Compliance Agent + main.py: Code review

Reviewed `a1_compliance_agent.py`, `pingpingostate.py` (state file), early `a2_seo_extraction_agent.py` draft, and `main.py`. Found:

- **A1:** placeholder paths (`folder_path`, `persist_directory`) never replaced with real paths; typo `retriever.inovke()` ‚Üí should be `.invoke()`.
- **A1's biggest gap:** the file only builds the retriever + `retriever_tool` ‚Äî there is no `compliance_node` function that actually calls the LLM, loops on tool calls, and writes `is_compliance` / `system_feedback` into state. This is what `main.py` was trying to import and it didn't exist yet.
- **A2 (early draft):** imported `persist_directory` from A1, which caused A1's entire PDF-loading + Chroma-build code to re-execute every time A2 was imported (module-level side effect ‚Äî fixed today by moving to a guarded/function-based setup).
- **main.py:** `langgrah` typo; `add_edge()` misused with a function instead of two node-name strings; **no conditional edge after `compliance_check`** ‚Äî was a flat unconditional edge straight to `seo_extraction`, which contradicts the design (non-compliant SKUs should `END` immediately, not proceed); no `workflow.compile()` anywhere.

